segments.text: And I don't know what she charged, but she was making some nickels and dimes for the two.
And I recall that Darnell, she wasn't no fancy dresser or anything.
They had some glad rags I guess you'd call it.
You know, studying all the time.
Everett Besh was so good, you know, he had a memory that he graduated with honors.
And I had heard that when he graduated he went to some university as head of some department because of his ability.
And Wallace Larson, he was from San Antonio, he opened up his place.
He did pretty well with the ranchers.
And Louis Springer, his mother had to come down and be close to her son.
We used to laugh because when Louis Springer's wife and my wife got together,
they were going to go to Bryan, to Safeways or Atlantic Pacific.
And this little old lady, she looked out the window, where are you going?
Oh we're going to get some whatever.
All right, wait just a minute, I'm going with you.
And my wife was looking and we couldn't tell her no, so here she comes.
So we remember that lady because of that.
Well, she had no friends, you know, and she didn't want to be alone all the time.
All right, so that first year, your wife then stayed home and took care of your five-year-old.
Yes, because of the unavailability of housing.
And there wasn't kindergarten.
No, no, I'm talking about when you all got here.
in Vet Village.
She didn't have a full-time job.
No, he did not have a full-time job.
And so she took care of him.
Did you have a nickname by that time?
Yeah.
They called me Quate.
Quate?
Yeah.
Q-U-A-T?
Oh, you could say C-U-A-T-E.
Right.
What does that mean?
That means close friend.
Oh, Quate, Quate.
Did almost all of the veterans have nicknames?
Well, no.
Not that I recall.
Some of those veterans were, what's the word I want to use?
They would see these young freshmen and they wanted nothing to do with them.
They didn't believe in it.
They said, we've been out there, we've risked our lives all these years during the war for you guys, and for me to take a lot of bluffs from you guys?
No.
And they would not associate with them.
I didn't feel that way.
I said, hey, I need them.
And so we got along fine.
All right.
After you moved then into College View, did you and your wife attend the college functions?
Did you all go to events on the campus then?
Not, no.
Didn't go to Guy and Hall movies?
Oh, yeah.
We went to the movies, yes.
How did you get that job at Guy and Hall?
Well, I had a friend named Stotzenberg, and his sister was married to a chemistry major.
And the girl, his sister, worked at Gine Hall at the box office.
She sold the tickets.
He had some, he had some tickets, and he says, I'm going to guide.
I got a new ticket, you want to come along?
Yeah, I'll come along.
And I heard something, you know, looking in my head.
He said, I want to talk to the manager of that place or something.
I want to get my foot in the door.
So I went.
Fair enough.
I met Mr. Tom Putty.
Tom Putty was a real slim fella.
He had three daughters and a wife.
And his three daughters finally married Aggies.
Now Tom Putty was the manager of Garn Hall and he did the sign writing for the movies that were coming.
He was good at it with the watercolor.
He had six cents, if you want to call that, of how many fixed cameras.
I mean, he could fix cameras, and almost every day the mailman would deliver a package of a camera that was defective from some guy somewhere away, you know.
And he'd say, fix it, and I'd tell him to send me the bill.
He took pictures of the ring dance and worked all night in the basement.
One day I went into the basement and it was dark and I fell down a hole.
Yes.
And I didn't get hurt.
My boy would just scare the fool out of me.
And then I noticed one time there was some elderly men and they turned on the lights and they had a table like this one.
little locomotive trains, you know.
Toy train.
Yeah.
And it was elaborate.
I said, my God.
Well, that's a hobby with them, you know.
So I got to meet Mr. Putty.
And we talked.
He was real nice.
He said, Mr. Putty, I need a job, a part-time job.
And what did I do?
get a job here, doing something, anything.
He said, well look, I got all the help I need.
You come see me next semester.
This was in April.
So I gave my name and everything.
So one of the cadets, a senior, had to go to summer camp.
Not in May, but in April.
He was a projectionist.
So, lo and behold, when this cadet had to leave, Mr. Putty sent word for me.
Was that every night?
No, no.
That you were to work over there?
Yeah, I was to work over there, I think it was two afternoons a week.
So he showed me how to thread and join him.
And so I got by in the month of May.
Then of course, you know, summer, they closed it.
So from then on, I had a regular part-time job.
Do you remember what the pay was for that part-time job?
Yes, 50 cents a week.
I mean, 50 cents an hour, I'm sorry.
An hour, 50 cents an hour.
And it was up on the second stoop.
Well, I say second stoop because it was high.
And it only had two windows about this wide.
And the fumes from the ark were getting to me.
So I said, hey, I've got to get out of here.
And he put me somewhere else.
He said, oh, you take the popcorn concession.
candy, popcorn, this kind of thing.
And I said, hey, that's fine.
And then, at night, I would go to three places to put up my billboards for the movies the next day.
And so, all in total,
getting ready to graduate, I was not earning 80 cents an hour.
That was big money then, too.
And there was no tax withholding, nothing like that then.
Oh, brother, it was something.
And during the, when they were building the bonfire and logs, you know, I would be challenged, you know, when I'd go out at night to put up my billboards.
And I had to show the secretary who I was, where I am.
because they didn't want nothing to happen to that fall fire.
But they did.
One evening this plane came over.
You remember that?
No, but I've heard about it.
Describe it.
The way it got to be, see, this plane came over, it was a light plane.
And they had one of those score cans, five gallon, with gasoline and a wick.
And this plane was supposed to come low, light the wick, and let this can hit the following, set it on fire.
What these two guys in this plane didn't know, that it takes about 30,000 gallons of naphtha to set this pile of raw material.
Well, anyway, it flew low.
It dropped its can with the wig, but it missed the logs.
I don't know how far it was.
And that was the talk of the day the next day, you know.
And that was something.
Now, during those years in College View, what was your normal daily routine?
What time did you get up?
What chores did you do at the apartment?
And what did you do all day?
Well, trash started at noon o'clock.
And I had to get up at about 6 o'clock in the morning, get everything ready, and go back on campus.
We were having classes in what they called, well, there's different places.
And I had a tag on my car, so I had a certain place where I could park.
The KKs were just everywhere.
And if you got, I think it was three tickets, and you couldn't explain why, then you were barred.
You couldn't drive your car in.
You walked, or somebody else gave you a ride.
Okay, so I'm going to go to classes.
If the next class didn't start for another hour, I was hit for the library or someplace where I could read up and be prepared.
And so then the classes were over by noon, and so I did go back to the house.
And if I had an afternoon class, well, I had to come back.
Otherwise, I'd stay.
there where we were staying.
And study all afternoon?
Study all afternoon, unless I had a part-time job somewhere where it was study, study, study.
Now, did the GI Bill and what you were able to earn while you were here, did it pay for everything?
Yes.
Yeah, I had a ticket, and that was to buy supplies, you know, notebooks, pencils.
I'd just get what I needed, and then the clerk at the bookstore, they had a punch, you know, and they'd say, well, you got a dollar and a half worth of stuff.
And then when the, when that card was all, put a hold, you know, no more, that was it, no more.
Somebody figured out how much supplies you would need, see.
Now how did you become acquainted with A&M traditions and ceremonies and all the routine at A&M?
There wasn't any orientation for you veterans, was there?
No.
Not one orientation.
Do you remember going to your first silver taps?
I didn't go to silver taps.
You didn't go to Silver Taps while you were an undergraduate, ever?
No.
Oh, yes.
I went when we were at the annex.
Yeah, but once you came to the campus.
Oh, yes.
What was your impression when you went to Silver Taps?
Well, I could understand that there was a feeling, and that was fear of binding with the present students.
And the old students, there was a spirit of cohesion, if you will, that you just couldn't forget about it.
And this is what the class did last year here for us.
Now it's up to us to do it and keep up the tradition.
And I had heard through my in-laws that, hey, there's Aggies all over the world.
I says, you can go someplace.
And you meet up with an Aggie, and five minutes later, hey, you're old friends.
And you don't see that with Baylor or Texas Tech or those others.
And this is a friendship that's everlasting.
And so when y'all were living in College View, you brought your wife and your little boy, and you went to Silver Taps.
Did y'all go to midnight yell practice?
Maybe once or twice.
Did you help work on Bonfire ever?
Work on Bonfire?
No, no.
That was strictly for the Corps of Cadets.
I'm sure that, well that's all I saw.
And I don't think that ever would have turned me down, you know.
But I said, well they've got enough help.
And I see all those cranes and everything out there.
So I never volunteered, I just said.
You older veterans, did sometimes the younger undergraduates kind of look at you with envy or give you a hard, did they ever seem jealous that y'all were so much older and so much more mature?
There were times like that, yes.
They didn't come out and say so, but I could sense it, you know.
They couldn't get used to having older students there when they were used to seeing the younger ones together.
They were a little miles apart.
As you began to understand A&M,
Describe the way people were treated as students by other students.
Did it matter who your parents were, where you came from, what your background was?
No, sir.
It seemed like all the barriers just dropped.
Everybody was an Aggie.
There was never a bad Aggie.
All Aggies are good.
And once a year,
See, Bolton at one time, when we were freshmen, Bolton told us, all of us, the veterans, he says, if you don't learn anything, you learn how to meet people.
And it's true to this day.
And I watched those juniors and seniors when they go up there and they shake hands, see?
And I couldn't understand.
I said, why did they go like this?
My name's Jerk.
He said, well, when they go up to a freshman, Harley Fitz Jones, and he hits a brace.
And you're trying to grab him and get him off balance.
Oh, that's it.
And to this day, I still do that.
And sometimes when I meet one for the first time, an Aggie, I knew you were an Aggie.
the way you shook hands.
And the fact that you were Hispanic never was any disadvantage?
No.
I think no, there was no disadvantage really.
At the time I was there, there were very few Hispanics.
Aside from those that came from Mexico or Uruguay, that was a different breed.
And the ones that were from the state of Texas or someplace else, they were, seemed to be down here for business, to get that education, and there was no
animosities or any, you know.
Now, what did you and your wife and your youngster do for relaxation?
What did you all do for enjoyment?
Well, I didn't, my wife made friends with the other wives, and my little boy had to play with the other kids.
I tell you, it was heartbreaking for me.
When we came over to that village, he had an old bicycle, and one of the wheels had lost a rubber tire.
And the other kids, they had some nice tricycles.
So we went down to Bryan, Westonado, and they had toys.
a little bicycle with a chain on it that I wanted to get for Robert so he wouldn't feel isolated from the others because he had a junk tricycle.
So the manager was named Mr. Daniels.
And I didn't take offense to what he said.
He let me open an account and I would pay him
I think it was $5 a month.
And a bicycle cost, I think it was $25 or $27.50.
And he says, you will pay me, won't you?
I said, yes, sir.
He said, I'll pay my bills.
It's OK.
So I figured, he thought I was going to skip town.
So I did.
I paid it.
Paid it in full.
That was the only time, see.
I said, no, he wasn't being antisocial.
He must have been suffering some losses from people that are coming to A&M, and they flunk, and they leave, and then he's holding sacks.
Other than that, no.
And my wife could make friends anywhere she could go.
And so it was okay then.
All right.
At the end of that first year at College View,
Did you all go back to San Antonio that next summer?
I think we did.
Well, one summer I stayed and worked at the Grove.
At the Grove?
At the Grove, yeah.
And Mr. Putty was the one that showed the movies, and I had the concession for the popcorn and peanuts.
Ten cents a bag, and I'll never forget that, because when I turned in the money, it was all dimes.
Everybody had a dime.
Oh, I tell you, it was something.
Let's see, I'm trying to think of...
This says that in the summer of 51, you went back to San Antonio,
and then came back that fall in the new part of College View.
Yes, sir.
What kind of automobile did you have by then?
It was a 1940 Chevrolet.
It was a two-door.
Once or twice, my son was going to
A&M Consolidated Elementary School.
And the school had a bus.
They would come by and pick up the kids, see?
Well, my son wanted to get on the bus, so we'd give him his nickel to get on the bus.
And this morning, he missed it.
Oh, he felt bad.
Daddy, I don't want to get on the bus.
So I said, all right, get in the car.
So we followed the bus, and we passed the bus by two blocks, and I let him off.
Then the bus had to stop and pick him off over there.
I guess the driver was the one that said, well, this kid's over here.
He belongs in College Field.
He paid his nickel.
But, see, he had his little friends on that bus, too, see.
And as far as you know, his experiences at A&M Consolidated were all positive?
Oh, yes.
And I said, oh.
I remember when we were at College View, when the band left their area to go practice on Kyle Field, they'd play.
And man, all those kids would come out of the house and look at the band and follow the band.
There was something about the band that just, you know, makes... Did you and your wife and your son go to Bonfire?
Yes.
And what was your impression of Bonfire then?
Well, at first, I got a thrill out of it.
Like a fool, we wanted to get up there close.
And when that thing lit, boy, we had a retreat.
After that, you know, it was, you know, second nature, was it?
But the young people, they loved it.
Because they had the girlfriends, you know, and all this.
And to them, well, it was a chance to be with a girl and all this.
And they just loved that.
That was an excuse to get out and have some fun.
Old guys like me, Barrett says, well, the first one, that's okay.
That's just like eating apples.
After you eat the third one, it doesn't taste as good as the first one.
Now, Bonfire was held on the drill field then?
In front of where the MSC is now?
No.
Not on the drill field.
It wasn't held on the drill field?
No.
Oh, here.
Behind where Duncan is?
Yeah.
Okay.
Yes, sir.
Okay.
Because for a few years it was on the drill field, and I didn't know when it moved.
Let's see.
Did you all go to yell practice, midnight yell practice?
I don't recall.
Did you go to football games?
Oh, yes.
What was it like for an older veteran and his wife to go to a football game?
Well, give me that again.
No, I was saying what was it like for you as an older student?
You know, you weren't an 18- or 19-year-old.
You were mature.
Well, to be truthful,
I had never seen a college football game.
And this was the thrill, see.
And over there, the last row, there was like a wall.
And I'd take my son, and I'd sit him up there.
I thought I had to hold him.
And I remember one fellow, he was selling Coca-Cola.
In those days, it was in a bottle.
And they were just semi-cold.
You had to have something to drink.
And he had these cases, wooden cases of Coca-Cola.
And he was selling this by the bottle.
I forget what the cost.
And someone said, you see that fellow over there?
He's selling coats, you know?
And he's working his way to a college.
I said, you mean?
Whatever he makes, that's what he has to pay.
Boy, he must sell a lot of coats.
Yes.
And let's see, your practice, what about the Aggie band?
How did that impress you?
Oh, I tell you, it gets that big goose pimples in my arm.
Did you all go to any out-of-town football games?
You and your wife?
I don't recall.
No, sir.
Let's see.
Did you join a church here?
Yes.
Where?
We went to the First Baptist Church in College Station.
In College Station, not in Bryan?
No, we visited over there in Bryan.
But here?
But here, with Brother Longshore.
Remember Longshore?
Okay.
And what led you to that particular church?
I think Rachel had some friend that suggested it, and then it was closer to go here than to go on the way to Bryan.
And the people, we didn't know nobody in Bryan, but we knew some people over here.
In fact, we knew some of the ushers.
One of them had a cleaning place over here on South Gate.
I can't remember his name.
And so it was more of a friendly atmosphere, whether you like it or not.
So we stayed, we stayed for preaching, and it was, we enjoyed it.
And Mrs. Marion Pugh, she taught the little ones, and my son was there.
He would use some of the terms.
And in the morning time, we still kid him about that.
And Varian Pugh was in my class.
Do you remember Flake Fisher?
Okay, Flake Fisher was in my Sunday School class also.
Let's see, the MSC was being built during this time?
Yeah, it was just being built.
As a memorial to the World War II veterans, yes, sir.
But Guyon Hall was still the big place for the important events.
Oh, yeah.
Do you remember any important celebrity visitors that came while you were a student?
Well, yeah, there was a... Did Eisenhower come during that?
Oh, yeah, Eisenhower was here.
He visited here.
And...
there was a dance or something, and a named band, they would give a concert at Guyon, see, for those people that didn't want to, they were not going to attend the other function.
And this band, there was Glenn Gray, his Casa Loma Orchestra, he was here.
And Glenn Gray met
I said, Rachel's sister.
And he liked her.
And he says, say, do you sing?
I need a singer.
And God I just, who asked you that?
Glenn Gray.
And then there was Billy something, he had a band.
I don't recall their last name.
And they had left the instruments there on the stage in the afternoon.
And some kid took a trumpet and he was going to blow it and he took it home somewhere and the K.K.
's were looking for that kid and they knew who it was, see?
Billy, Billy something.
Okay.
And then who else?
There was another band that came down.
Did the Dorseys?
No.
I don't remember that one.
